So I'll just copy paste some of the Term glossary here:

>Harsist (Har-sis-t): A planet that is divided by several layers of habitable zones, and is said to be one of the most prosperous planets in all of Bootes.

>Tarven (Tar-vin): A species of bipedal bovine people that inhabit the third layer, Minnven (Men-vin), and adjusted to the colder climates of this layer. The Tarven grew from their nomadic roots and started a renaissance that birthed a new prosperous age that sought to unify the three nations. There are three subspecies of Tarven: Rinnus- akin to cattle that bear semblance to Bos Tarus breeds, and live between the northern tundra and dark forests of Minnven; Inndus- akin to cattle that bear semblance to Bos Indicus breeds, and live between the deserts and temperate forests of eastern Minnven; Yannik- akin to Yaks and Buffalo, these people live between the plains, and redwood forests of west Minnven. While wars were fought and prejudice ensued, the reserved Tarven people have managed to create three functioning nations that have strove to better the whole of their species. This push has lead the Galactic Federation to consider the Tarven people as huge contributors in exported goods, but a fellow species, The Khab, jealously wages campaigns to destroy them and other species of Harssist.

Anonymous Tue 30 May 2023 05:32:34 No.56892845 Report
Quoted By: >>56892902 >>56893886
>>56892403
Not trying to be an asshole here. I'm just saying, that seems like an awful lot of odd-sounding stuff to get to "okay there are cow people and the girls are cute." I'm still not sure I'm parsing all of it. "Layers of habitable zones?" Like the Hollow Earth and all that Shaver Mystery stuff?

Also, and I hate to keep changing direction on you, but where did these people come from? Was this planet seeded with life from Earth? Because redwood forests, and all that. Did some aliens in the distant past genetically engineer cow people to be slaves, or something?

You talk about this planet, which is in "Bootes." What' does that mean in this context? There's a constellation with that name but the stars in it are spread out, some of them fewer than 25 light-years from Earth, some almost nine hundred light-years away. Are we describing this place as being in a particular region of the galaxy? Calling it part of a constellation is only meaningful if we are only concerned with what region of the sky it appears in as viewed from Earth.

Lastly, how similar are these creatures to humans, psychologically? Are observations of human nature and human history generalizable to them? Because "functioning nations that have strove to better the whole of their species" are not a common phenomenon in human history.

Overall I am looking at this and not sure what you're going for. Hollow Earth stuff is pretty much strictly a worldbuilding detail that got thrown into weird high fantasy stories printed in pulp paper magazines between the World Wars, back when a lot of the people who bought those magazines thought in terms of globes with big blank patches labeled "UNEXPLORED." It's a concept that doesn't really resonate with readers a hundred years later, and it doesn't really fit in with this "prosperous planet" and "Galactic Federation" stuff, which imply a high-tech starfaring civilization. Maybe I'm reading it all wrong, of course.

I didn't think of it as a Hollow Earth type thing when starting this. I thought of it to be several large continents that orbited around a small planetoid and core; I can understand the comparison as Agartha too has multiple layers.
So Harsist has a couple of various sentient species that begun life on the outer crust. A chaotic event separated the planet's crust causing it to be known as the Layered planet from the results. The life on this planet resides in environments that have some semblance to Earth's biomes, and The Tarven naturally evolved from a intelligent herbivore (It was similar to a Gerenuk) that roamed the norther continents.

Harsist resides in a galaxy that borders close to Bootes Void or Barnard 68.

So I took a cow and thought about how it would look as a sentient being, also I took inspiration from species that carried some relation to that design: Sangheili, Quarians, and whatever Shyni from Teraurge is. I'd say their 75% similar with minor vestigial traits and a tail.
So they have the idea of a being's nature and history figured out, but it's different to what we Humans do. Also them having a somewhat unified whole is based on Earth cattle and how sociable/ passive they are. There were wars, but not to the extent of Humans.

Anonymous Tue 30 May 2023 21:39:30 No.56907440 Report
Quoted By: >>56915670
>>56907068
Also the factor that forces vertebrate populations back to a 1:1 sex ratio isn't how often males can impregnate females. It's the fact that when a male is born with the fluke tendency to produce sperm cells of mostly one sex, let's say, his little swimmers all bear the Y chromosome, or nearly all. His kids are mostly male. Suddenly there's a strong evolutionary advantage for the guy who produces sperm cells that mostly carry X chromosomes and produce females. In populations of more than a few hundred it always swings back into 1:1 balance or within margin of error of it very rapidly. That's Fisher's Principle. Males who impregnate females with only one gender offspring create great advantages and enormous reproductive success for males who produce only the opposite gender, immediately, always. This isn't perfectly universal among vertebrates but it's pretty close.

I guess you could have a society where a small number of rich guys monopolize all the women, but the other 99% of men have every reason to revolt and no rational reason to support such a system. That is probably why, historically speaking, we don't see that kind of thing very much.
